<TEXT>
seventyseven japanese left by ship for sakhalin 
today becoming the first group of japanese tourists to visit the 
soviet island since the end of world war ii local officials said 
tatsuo hamamori mayor of wakkanai on japans northernmost 
island of hokkaido was among the tourists who left the city for 
kholmsk a city on southern sakhalin aboard a soviet ship this 
morning 
i hope todays voyage will pave the way for a regular ferry 
service linking japan with the soviet island and which will 
contribute to promoting exchanges of people culture and goods 
hamamori said in a nationally televised interview before the ships 
departure 
a territorial dispute over a group of islands near sakhalin 
seized by the soviets in the closing days of the world war ii has 
blocked efforts to conclude a japansoviet peace treaty 
technically leaving the two nations at war 
the soviet claim to sakhalin is not now disputed by japan but 
total recognition is being withheld by the government until the 
return of the other islands known in japan as the northern 
territories 
though this is the first group of tourists allowed entry 
relatives of japanese buried on sakhalin have in the past been 
allowed to visit the island 
the times travel agency a private japanese tourist agency 
sponsoring the tour said seven more trips from wakkanai are 
scheduled this year it said the tourists will tour the southern 
part of sakhalin during their fiveday stay 
last monday some 240 japanese tourists left from a separate 
japanese city by ship for vladivostok a major soviet far east 
port also for the first time since 1945 
</TEXT>
