<TEXT>
a new agriculture department analysis shows 
that farmers and ranchers with cowcalf operations the foundation 
herds that form the bedrock of the nations beef business will 
probably make money again this year 
but the detailed figures by the departments economic research 
service include some sour notes regarding capital improvements that 
could affect the longterm financial health of the cattle industry 
the analysis also includes some mixed outlook figures for hog 
producers who saw market prices drop sharply last year even sheep 
producers are feeling a pinch 
if only cash flow is considered the cowcalf operators are in 
pretty good shape economists hosein shakpouri and terry crawford 
said in their report but when costs of capital replacement are 
included the situation is much less encouraging 
the report compares estimated 1988 production costs and net 
returns with those projected for 1989 
last years drought severely affected all livestock 
producers the report said spending on feed jumped 28 percent from 
1987 while gross cash receipts from livestock sales increased only 
3 percent 
on the average the gross value of production of one beef 
cow totaled 34818 in 1988 that was up from 31370 in 1987 the 
projection for 1989 is 34606 per cow 
the values were construed by including allowances for calves and 
culled cows and converting them to a onecow figure 
cash expenses ranging from feed to taxes insurance and 
interest also were prorated on a onecow basis those added up to 
29677 last year up from 25584 in 1987 the projection for 1989 
is 30626 per cow 
thus after deducting cash expenses from gross values the 
cowcalf operator this year may have an average cash return of 
3980 per cow down from 5046 in 1988 and 5786 in 1987 the 
report showed 
but if an allowance for capital replacement of buildings 
equipment and other facilities is included the tidy percow net 
profit disappears in this case the report said the operator 
could lose an average of 4179 per cow in 1989 compared with 
losses of 2669 in 1988 and 1772 in 1987 
cash returns before and after a charge for the replacement 
capital are key indicators of producer supply response the 
report said a positive cash return is an incentive for producers 
to continue or even expand their operation a negative cash return 
is often regarded as a signal to discontinue production 
however the report added the figures are averages and there 
are producers who fare better or worse some individual operators 
may expand when most do not also they can make substitutions in 
production items in different proportions than allowed in the 
analysis 
the cash return or residual reflects the cash flow available 
for paying family living expenses repaying debts and replacing 
machinery equipment and buildings 
in the shortterm producers may defer machinery and equipment 
purchases or repairs if the farm is producing little income or is 
in an unfavorable tax position the report said but over the 
long run operators must replace and maintain the buildings and 
equipment typically used in the operation 
the report said the projected decline in net returns to cowcalf 
operators this year is due primarily to higher wintering 
expenses higher feed costs and a small increase in the market 
price of fed beef would lower the price cattle feeders can pay 
for feeder cattle in 1989 which will help depress cowcalf 
returns 
looking at the hog situation the report said farrowtofinish 
operators who account for about 80 percent of the slaughter hogs 
produced saw 1988 gross value of production drop to an equivalent 
of 4287 per 100 pounds from 5130 per hundredweight in 1987 
this years value was projected at 4123 
cash expenses meanwhile jumped to 4164 per hundredweight in 
1988 from 3407 in 1987 this year cash expenses were projected at 
an equivalent of 4444 per hundredweight 
consequently last years cash return to farrowtofinish 
operators averaged 123 per hundredweight down from 1723 in 
1987 this year hog farmers are expected to lose 321 per 
hundredweight 
after allowing for capital replacement hog producers lost 589 
per hundredweight in 1988 compared with a profit of 1034 in 
1987 this years loss was shown at 1064 per hundredweight 
sheep production has consistently been one of the most 
profitable livestock enterprises in the past 18 years the report 
said nevertheless us sheep producers experienced a sharp 
decline in their cash returns in 1988 as sheep production 
increased higher feed costs as well as lower lamb prices eroded 
their financial positions 
the average value of sheep production 1988 was reported at 
6556 per ewe in 1988 down from 7305 in 1987 the value for 
1989 was projected at 6398 per ewe cash expenses were 4638 in 
1988 4466 in 1987 and projected at 4767 in 1989 
as a result net cash returns averaged 1918 per ewe in 1988 
compared with 2839 in 1987 and a 1989 return projected at 1631 
with allowances for capital replacement sheep producers were 
shown at a profit of 1112 per ewe in 1988 and 2060 in 1987 the 
projection for 1989 was 790 per ewe 
</TEXT>
