<TEXT>
the peoples liberation army once rooted in 
rigid communist ideology was making a transition from 
revolutionary force to modern army when it was confronted by the 
surprising strength of the prodemocracy movement 
although the imposition of martial law makes the demonstrations 
in beijing illegal solidiers have been reluctant unable or 
ordered not to halt them 
young soldiers waiting in convoys on the outskirts of the 
capital took cigarettes and drinks from protesters and listened 
intently as students lectured them on the campaign for democratic 
reform some flashed vforvictory signs when their trucks 
retreated away from the city 
it has become even harder to decipher how senior military 
officers were reacting to the most serious challenge to the social 
order the communist party has faced in its 40year rule 
senior leader deng xiaopings one remaining official post is as 
head of the central military commission and it is believed to have 
been deng who ordered the crackdown on the student movement 
the 84yearold deng is certain to have the support of other 
older officers who served in the old red army and continue to 
regard the peoples liberation army as the last bastion of 
revolutionary integrity 
less certain is the backing of younger officers the plas new 
ranks of professionals who may share some of the students concerns 
about the slow pace of political reform in china 
the pla played a major role in restoring order during the 
chaotic 196676 cultural revolution when fighting between 
different leftist factions brought china to the brink of civil war 
since then however the nations trust in the ideological 
purity of the pla has begun to slip 
in the early 1980s the army abandoned mao tsetungs concept of 
a guerrilla peoples war in which the army would beat back an 
attacker through sheer numbers and revolutionary fervor 
deng has reduced the number of troops by about 1 million since 
1985 when china fielded 42 million soldiers he has brought back 
a ranking system abandoned for 23 years emphasized better training 
and sought to create a modern military force 
the pla however has been saddled with severe budgetary 
restrictions as government funds were channeled to economic 
modernization programs about twothirds of defense industry 
factories have been switched to making civilian goods to help boost 
national production and exports 
from 1950 to 1980 defense spending accounted for 172 percent 
of chinas state expenditures the pla says in 1988 it received 
only 749 percent of the budget defense spending in actual terms 
is expected to fall about 6 percent this year after inflation 
in the past pla ranks were filled with young people attracted 
to the prestige of a military career and the possibility of 
escaping rural poverty pla members still command respect but the 
low pay and harsh living conditions have made recruiting more 
difficult 
in welloff rural areas families commonly pay off local 
officials to keep their sons off local quota lists for enlistment 
one recent report in the official media said the army is ending 
up with soldiers who are mentally retarded or illiterate or who 
have criminal records 
many recruits are eager to finish their term and return to 
civilian life so they can make money to buy the material comforts 
young people have come to expect such recruits are now listening 
with sympathy when students their own age chant the peoples army 
belongs to the people 
