<TEXT>
the supreme court today made deadlines for the 
filing of civil rights lawsuits by some prison inmates more 
flexible 
the court unanimously ruled in a case from michigan that states 
may give prisoners extra leeway on when they file such federal 
suits 
the justices reinstated a suit by tyrone victor hardin who said 
his rights were violated when for six months in 1980 and 1981 he 
was placed in solitary confinement at southern michigan state 
prison hardin said he became aware in july 1984 that prison rules 
entitled him to an administrative hearing before he was placed in 
solitary 
hardin representing himself filed a federal suit in 1986 but 
the judge threw out the case on the ground that michigan requires 
such a suit be filed within three years of the alleged injury 
the supreme court said today the judge also should have applied 
a michigan law which suspends the deadline for prisoners the law 
permits a suit to be filed within a year after the inmate is 
released 
justice john paul stevens in his opinion for the high court 
said suspending the deadline for inmates may be intended to help 
prisoneers loathe to bring suit against adversaries to whose 
daily supervision and control they remain subject 
stevens also said inmates as long as they remain confined may 
have great difficulty proving allegations that their rights were 
violated 
a states decision to suspend the deadline for filing suit in 
such cases is consistent with federal civil rights law aimed at 
protecting prisoners he said 
the case is hardin vs straub 877023 
</TEXT>
