<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to allow a san 
diego woman whose family died in a 1983 airplane crash to sue the 
federal government her city and a utility company in one federal 
lawsuit 
by a 54 vote the court ruled that barbara finley must sue san 
diego and the san diego gas and electric co in a separate state 
court case 
at issue was whether federal courts have the power to include as 
defendants in federal tort claims act suits against the government 
those whose alleged wrongdoing raise no constitutional or federal 
law issue the courts majority said no 
mrs finleys husband and two daughters were returning home to 
san diego in a private plane on nov 11 1983 
on his first approach to montgomery field near san diego the 
pilot was unable to land because the approach and runway lights 
were not visible and he was not authorized to attempt an 
instrument landing 
on the second approach the plane struck electric transmission 
lines owned and maintained by san diego gas and electric no one 
survived the resulting crash 
mrs finley first sued san diego and the utility in state court 
she contended that the city negligently had failed to maintain the 
runway approach lights and that the utility negligently had placed 
its lines too close to the runway and failed to provide warning 
beacons for them 
when she later discovered that the federal aviation 
administration was responsible for the runway lights mrs finley 
sued the government in federal court under the ftca 
she then asked a federal trial judge to add san diego and the 
utility company as defendants in the federal case 
the trial judge granted the request citing judicial economy 
and efficiency 
but the 9th us circuit court of appeals last year reversed the 
trial judge ruling that the city and utility could not be included 
as defendants in the federal case 
today the supreme court said in an opinion by justice antonin 
scalia that the appeals court was right 
but justices harry a blackmun john paul stevens william j 
brennan and thurgood marshall dissented 
the decision apparently leaves mrs finley free to pursue her 
state court suit against the city and the utility while suing the 
federal government in federal court 
the case is finely vs us 871973 
</TEXT>
