<TEXT>
the movement for political change grew from a 
tiny student poster campaign to a mass call for the removal of top 
chinese leaders in five weeks of unprecedented high drama 
chinas leadership could hardly have seen the trouble awaiting 
them when former communist party chief hu yaobang a relatively 
liberal leader who was ousted in a crackdown on a previous round of 
student demonstrations died of a heart attack april 15 
within hours of hus death posters sprang up at beijing 
university praising him and indirectly criticing the leaders who 
forced him to resign two years earlier the students held several 
demonstrations during the following week to press demands for 
democratic reform a free press and clean government 
events surrounding hus april 22 funeral set the tone for the 
following month of protest with students fearlessly defying 
security forces 
up to 100000 people gathered in central beijings tiananmen 
square april 21 to mourn hu and stayed overnight refusing to 
follow police orders to disperse 
top officials going to a memorial for hu the following day at 
the adjacent great hall of the people peered across a protective 
wall of thousands of soldiers to view fistwaving citizens 
demanding an end to what they called chinas dictatorship 
the broad support the student movement was winning from workers 
and others became obvious a week later when tens of thousands of 
people lined the streets of beijing to cheer about 150000 students 
marching for democracy along the route enthusiastic onlookers 
gave the marchers money food and water 
enthusiastic crowds again appeared the following week when 
students marched to mark the 70th anniversary of chinas first 
student movement for democracy but the campaign seemed to falter 
after the march ended as leaders argued over what tactics to take 
to press their demands 
while students at most colleges in the capital ended a twoweek 
class boycott beijing university students kept up the heat 
refusing to return to their classrooms and demanding more action 
about 3500 students many from the nations most prestigious 
schools decided to press their demands by staging a hunger strike 
at tiananmen beginning may 13 two days before the arrival of 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev to china to normalize ties 
after 30 years of icy relations 
the government urged the students to end the strike before 
gorbachevs arrival so as not to spoil the nations image students 
hotly debated what to do in the predawn hours of may 15 before 
deciding to continue their fast forcing several changes in the 
soviet leaders schedule that embarrassed the government 
as the fasting students health began to deteriorate beijing 
residents grew increasingly miffed at the governments failure to 
meet the hunger strikers demands of dialogue with officials and a 
retraction of an editorial that called the movement a 
disturbance 
in the largest protest of communist chinas 40year history 
well over 1 million people poured into downtown beijing on 
wednesday in support of the hunger strikers many called for the 
resignation of premier li peng viewed as a conservative and 
senior leader deng xiaoping demonstrations were reported in at 
least two dozen other chinese cities 
another mass protest the next day was answered by li with a 
hardline speech and the declaration of martial law in much of the 
capital throngs of workers rushing to tiananmen to protect the 
students yelled li peng step down and said his retirement 
was the only way the demonstrations would end 
communist party chief zhao ziyang a relative liberal 
sympathetic with many grievances raised by demonstrators 
reportedly has offered to resign although there has been no 
official announcement 
lis future also seems uncertain as he faces virtually 
universal condemnation from the people of beijing 
deng has not appeared publicly or been quoted by official media 
since he met gorbachev on may 16 
</TEXT>
