<TEXT>
the soviet supreme court said monday that citizens 
may not be thrown in jail for expressing truthful criticism of 
officials limiting the scope of a new decree widely criticized by 
reformers and dissidents alike 
the court reviewed a decree passed by the presidium of the 
supreme soviet on april 8 because citizens already have been 
arrested under differing interpretations of the law according to a 
report distributed by the tass news agency 
critics charged that a provision of the decree banning 
discrediting officials and government bodies was written in such a 
way that a person could be prosecuted for telling the unpleasant 
truth 
alvydas juozaidis a spokesman for lithuanias grassroots 
sajudis organization called the decree pure stalinism among 
its other critics were human rights activist andrei d sakharov 
some opponents have called for the congress of peoples 
deputies the new parliament that meets for the first time 
thursday to overturn the law 
the court said wellfounded argumentative criticism of the 
action and decisions of these organs and officials by citizens 
acting publicly in the framework of socialist law cannot be viewed 
as a criminally punishable act 
the courts action taken as president mikhail s gorbachev 
seeks to strengthen the role of law in soviet society constituted 
one of the rare times the court has acted to ensure a controversial 
measure is applied consistently 
the supreme court instructed lower courts the decree touched 
only intentional public distribution of slanderous inventions 
that undermines faith in officials 
it said that the decree did not include dispatches in the 
press and any other form of information reflecting insufficiencies 
in the activity of these organs social organizations and 
officials 
the court said its declaration was a balance between protecting 
officials from insults and slander and protecting the rights of 
individuals to express their views 
tass did not say how many criminal cases have been filed on the 
basis of the new law nor did it address any of them in detail 
but it said that in the month and a half since the decree was 
published differences in interpretation already had come to light 
soviet officials have said that the new decree is more specific 
and less subject to abuse than articles 70 and 190 of the criminal 
code that for years have banned antisoviet agitation and 
propaganda and antisoviet slander 
politically controled courts used those laws for years to 
imprison dissidents last year the soviet union said it intended to 
radically alter those laws it stopped arresting people under them 
and in the past two years has released hundreds of people arrested 
under them 
but dissidents and reformers alike reacted angrily to the 
decree claiming the provision against discrediting officials 
actually was worse than the previous law 
the law also bans public calls to overthrow the government and 
premeditated acts aimed at inciting national or racial 
animosity 
in other action that also expressed its desire to right the 
legal abuses of the past tass said the supreme court continued its 
rehabiliation who were unlawfully convicted of antisoviet activity 
in the 1930s through the 1960s 
those rehabiliated monday included former midlevel officials who 
were accused under josef stalin of being german spies or taking 
part in a conspiracy to kill the popular leningrad party chief 
sergei kirov in 1934 
a latvian poet ke skueniek who was convicted in 1962 of 
antisoviet agitation also was cleared 
</TEXT>
