<TEXT>
the cape hatteras lighthouse has symbolized 
the rugged beauty of north carolinas outer banks islands for 
generations and now the tower that warned ships of dangerous 
shoals is itself threatened by the sea 
for years debate has raged about what should be done to 
preserve the nations oldest and tallest brick lighthouse 
when it was built in 1870 replacing one that had fallen into 
the sea the 208foot lighthouse was 1500 feet from the atlantic 
ocean the shoreline has advanced about 11 feet per year since then 
and waves now crash less than 200 feet from its base 
the future of the landmark was left uncertain again last week 
when the national park services regional office in atlanta said it 
was putting off a decision on how to preserve the tower 
instead the park service said it plans to issue a special 
document listing options for protecting the lighthouse in about 
three weeks then the agency will accept public comment for 30 to 
90 days before making a final decision 
were trying to determine whether the comment cries out for 
hearings or meetings said james howard a park service spokesman 
over the years a number of efforts including steel groins and 
artificial seaweed to hold sand have done little to slow the 
seas natural advance 
in 1986 the us army corps of engineers was set to build a 
23foothigh revetment and seawall around the spire at a cost of 
56 million 
but a group calling itself the move the lighthouse committee 
persuaded the park service to reconsider saying the ocean would 
eventually surround the lighthouse making it an island 
last year a panel of the national academy of sciences 
recommended the 2600ton lighthouse be moved inland the panel of 
10 experts estimated that moving the lighthouse 500 feet on rails 
would cost 46 million and take a year 
if you want to save the lighthouse there is absolutely no 
alternative said orrin pilkey a professor of geology at duke 
university and a member of the move the lighthouse committee 
but many residents of hatteras island fear the monument will 
collapse if it is moved instead they favor efforts to replenish 
the beaches using sand fences and more artificial seaweed or 
groins 
the academy of sciences committee acknowledged some detrimental 
effects of relocating the lighthouse as many as eight acres of 
ancient maritime forest in adjacent buxton woods could be lost in 
clearing a new site they said 
if they move it were going to lose something whether it falls 
or not because it wont be on the same site it was built on said 
rany jennette whose father was the last civilian keeper of the 
cape hatteras light 
jennette who was born in the adjacent lighthouse keepers 
quarters in 1921 comes up from his home in greenville sc every 
summer to work as a seasonal ranger and tour guide 
i would go up to the top any time my father would let me he 
said one thing i really enjoyed was using the old heavy 
spyglasses to watch the ships go by 
</TEXT>
