<TEXT>
a man charged with conspiring to ship 
explosives to the philippines in 1981 to help depose thenpresident 
ferdinand marcos was framed his lawyer argued monday 
attorney james brosnahan made the allegation during opening 
arguments in the longawaited trial of steven psinakis 
the case has generated protests from current leaders in the 
philippines where psinakis is considered a hero 
more than 100 philippine lawmakers have urged president bush to 
block the prosecution and president corazon aquino interceded 
personally to get psinakis freed on 200000 bail the presidents 
brotherinlaw sen agapito aquino has said he will seek removal 
of us military bases from the philippines if psinakis is 
convicted 
psinakis 57 a greekborn us citizen has denied any role in 
bombmaking and has said he is being prosecuted because of a 
vendetta against him by the local fbi and federal prosecutors he 
declined to make any statement monday 
prosecutors said pieces of explosive detonator cord bombmaking 
materials and shipping documents were found in a search of garbage 
at psinakis home in december 1981 
but brosnahan told jurors psinakis was framed it was planted 
there and the question is by whom 
he said psinakis never purchased never sent never 
transported and never received detonating cord in interstate 
commerce without a permit 
in a news conference outside the courtroom brosnahan said 
psinakis had become the target of threats by marcos agents and 
supporters he was told somebody was going to get him and he was 
told that repeatedly he said 
brosnahan drew heated objections from assistant us attorney 
ben burch when he tried to detail events in the philippines in the 
70s and 80s said that psinakis codefendant charles avila is 
now a mayor in a philippine city and described psinakis efforts 
to persuade us authorities that marcos agents were committing 
crimes here avila has remained in the philippines which has no 
extradition treaty with the united states 
burch said the prosecution will play two wiretapped telephone 
conversations between psinakis and a st louis doctor active in the 
antimarcos movement in the calls he said the men used the code 
terms of 50s and 60s and 30s to refer to explosive detonator 
cord and its size 
shipments of explosive cord from st louis to san francisco were 
picked up at a bus station by a friend of psinakis he said then 
delivered to someone in the psinakis family 
burch said investigators searching the psinakis home found a 
letter addressed dearest buddy discussed bcs or blasting 
caps stripping the rope a process used to get the explosive 
material from the detonator cord and a shortage of powdered 
sugar he said the letter typed on psinakis typewriter was 
signed steve 
psinakis wife presentacion comes from a prominent philippine 
family allegedly robbed of its riches by marcos the couple moved 
to san francisco in 1973 after marcos went into exile three years 
ago psinakis returned to the philippines a hero 
psinakis was indicted secretly in december 1986 and arrested the 
following july on arrival at san francisco international airport 
if convicted of conspiracy and aiding and abetting in the 
shipment of explosives from st louis to san francisco psinakis 
faces up to 15 years in prison and 20000 in fines 
</TEXT>
