<DOCNO> AP890522-0209 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
about 100 armed men boarded a train 
carrying 1500 tons of emergency food supplies to the warravaged 
south and robbed three relief workers a government statement said 
monday 
it said three western relief officials were robbed of their 
personal belongings but were not harmed and the gunmen left 
without touching the food supplies it did not give the names or 
nationalities of the officials working with the unsponsored 
relief project 
it reported the robbers boarded the train sunday about nine 
miles north of malwal and said they were searching for foreigners 
after holding the three officials briefly as hostages the gunmen 
left and told the train crew to continue the trip to aweil 
according to the statement it gave no other details 
the train started the journey saturday after a delay of more 
than a month caused in part by crewmen who feared making the trip 
through the embattled area without an armed escort 
it left muglad in southwestern sudan for aweil a town 180 miles 
farther south that is controlled by government troops 
the train with 48 freight cars is scheduled to drop off the 
loads from 32 cars in malwal and maput two rebelheld towns 
between muglad and aweil 
it had been schedluled to depart april 15 a further delay was 
caused by government objections to the plan to deliver food to 
areas held by the rebels sudan peoples liberation army 
organizing the shipment is operation lifeline sudan which is 
part of a un effort to help some 100000 people threatened with 
starvation 
the 132 million project was planned to stockpile 100000 tons 
of food in southern sudan by the end of this month but less than 
half of that amount has been delivered 
un officials have said the operation is a race against time 
seasonal rains that begin in may turn roads and airfields into 
quagmires 
the southern rebels mainly christians and animists have been 
battling for more than six years for greater autonomy and more 
economic development from the central government in khartoum the 
government and northern sudan are predominantly moslem 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

