<DOCNO> AP890522-0223 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
striking government doctors treated 
patients at makeshift clinics outside major hospitals and 
distributed free medicine monday as negotiations continued to end 
the weeklong walkout for more pay 
dr rohit parasher a strike leader said the clinics were 
established as an expression of our deep anguish and concern for 
our patients 
about 5000 doctors went on strike last tuesday and government 
hospitals began turning away many patients because of the lack of 
staff 
parasher said more than 4000 people have received treatment at 
the clinics set up in tents outside nine of new delhis 11 
hospitals 
medicine will be provided free and the clinics will be operated 
until the strike ends he said 
a health ministry official said negotiations are under way but 
he declined to give details 
earlier wage negotiations ended in deadlock may 15 and the next 
day more than 3500 doctors in delhi left their jobs about 1400 
doctors at government hospitals in chandigarh pondicherry banaras 
and aligarh joined the strike 
the strikers are seeking pay raises higher allowances for not 
being allowed to have private practices and firm schedules for 
promotions 
most are junior staffers and nearly all are resident physicians 
emergency cases are been handled by senior doctors 
the strikers want a montly increase of 53 they now receive 
between 200 and 269 per month 
they also seek an increase in the monthly allowance for not 
having a private practice from 16 to 40 government doctors are 
barred by law from having their own practice 
</TEXT>
