israelis lit hundreds of bonfires monday night 
to celebrate an ancient hebrew victory over the roman occupiers of 
the holy land 
the bonfires of the lag baomer holiday which ends at sundown 
tuesday commemorate the fires lit by the soldiers of simon 
barkochba who led jews in a rebellion against the romans between 
135 ad and 138 ad 
jewish legend also holds that lag baomer marks the end of a 
plague in which 24000 disciples of the famed rabbi akiva died 
because they did not properly honor one another 
another legend says akivas disciples died fighting the romans 
israeli children often make bows and arrows during the holiday to 
reenact the battle 
police estimated that about 200000 people mostly orthodox 
jews will spend the holiday at mount meron near the northern city 
of safed to celebrate lag baomer with picnics and prayers 
mount meron is the burial site of rabbi simeon baryohai 
believed to be the author of the zohar a central book in the 
mystical jewish teaching the kabbalah the kabbalists see lag 
baomer as the anniversary of baryohais death 
