<TEXT>
among the byzantine maneuverings of chinas 
political system one thing is clear power is strictly a party 
affair 
the main premise in chinese politics is that the communist party 
decides and the government does decisions are generally made by 
consensus among party leaders 
the legislature or national peoples congress has little pull 
and direct elections as known in the west are practically 
nonexistent 
the decisionmaking process is made murkier by the role of 
senior leader deng xiaoping 84 deng holds only one official post 
as chairman of the central military commission and has withdrawn 
from an active daytoday role in running the country 
but there has been no question that when critical matters arise 
dengs word is final that ultimate authority may now be on the 
line as opposition grows to the imposition of martial law believed 
done on dengs orders to put down studentled unrest in beijing 
the general course of the nation is adjusted about every five 
years when the 47 millionmember party convenes its national 
congress of about 2000 delegates 
the congress however merely reflects decisions made by the 
175member central committee which meets in full session at least 
once a year and the 17member politburo the nucleus of party 
power 
at the core of this nucleus is the fivemember standing 
committee of the politburo at dengs bidding the standing 
committee is now balanced with two advocates of reform party 
general secretary zhao ziyang and hu qili two more conservative 
politicians premier li peng and vice premier yao yilin and one 
fencesitter qiao shi 
chinas executive wing is the state council led by the premier 
and three vice premiers and including 41 ministers all are party 
members and the ranking officials such as li peng and the vice 
premiers are politburo members despite promises to separate party 
and government functions the party still has a decisive say in a 
broad spectrum of policy areas 
this is even more the case with the national peoples congress 
a body of almost 3000 which meets for about two weeks once a year 
to vote on legislature and formally appoint members of the state 
council it also fills the largely ceremonial post of president or 
head of state now held by retired gen yang shangkun 
the national peoples congress in recent years has tried to shed 
its image as a rubberstamp body by allowing more debate and 
seeking more say in shaping legislature 
the congress or more exactly its 163member standing committee 
which is responsible for its daytoday operations has managed to 
alter or delay some controversial bills 
but senior leadership in the congress called the highest 
organ of state power is again dominated by the party and all 
important legislation emerges from policies set by the party 
under the national peoples congress are peoples congresses at 
various district and provincial levels citizens have a direct vote 
for the lowestlevel county congresses although the candidates 
must generally be approved by the local party offices 
the local congresses consulting with the party appoint 
delegates to provinciallevel congresses who in turn nominate 
delegates for the national congress 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

