<TEXT>
if theres a deep black hole in south america 
bolivia has been in it but now as some of its more advanced 
neighbors might be on the verge of falling in bolivia may be 
coming out the light at the top offers hope for the poorest 
country on the continent but its still only a glimmer this is one 
in a series of periodic reports by the associated press on the 
economic social and political turbulence that has turned south 
america into a continent in crisis 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a remarkable economic turnaround and a 
newfound political stability are giving hope to the south american 
country that perhaps most needs it 
but despite bolivias visions of a brighter future its present 
remains bleak 
of every 10 workers two cant find jobs and one has turned to 
the illegal cocaine business 
one of every 10 newborns doesnt survive infancy the worst 
rate in the americas 
of every 1000 bolivians 14 die each year thats nearly 
double the south american average 
the new leadership that will grapple with the countrys grave 
problems wont be known until at least aug 4 when congress 
convenes to choose a new president in a general election may 7 
all candidates fell short of the absolute majority needed for 
direct election so the legislature must pick from the top three 
finishers gonzalo sanchez de lozada the former dictator hugo 
banzer suarez and jaime paz zamora 
all three have pledged however to stick with an economic 
program that transformed bolivia from south americas most chaotic 
nation into what some are calling a third world model 
bolivia has had 76 governments since independence from spain in 
1825 half of them de facto military governments and the other 
half democratically elected 
from 1978 to 1982 its 69 million people many of them 
descendants of an indian culture that predated inca conquests in 
bolivia by several centuries saw eight changes of government 
they included three bloody military coups 
democracy was reestablished in 1982 but the government of 
thenpresident hernan siles zuazo proved unable to reverse an 
economic tailspin and an inflation rate that soared to an 
inconceivable rate of 23000 percent a year 
a 10million peso note shrank in value to 5 and the central 
bank confessed to not a penny in reserves 
when president victor paz estenssoro was elected to replace 
siles zuazo in 1985 he declared simply but dramatically bolivia 
is dying on us 
his government prescribed a drastic cure a 95percent currency 
devaluation an end to subsidized prices and a 10fold increase in 
the price of gasoline and the layoff of 35000 state tin miners 
and other government employees while public spending was slashed 
an effective new tax system brought in additional revenues 
the new program was put to an immediate test when world market 
prices for tin and oil the countrys main exports plunged 
drastically the plan nonetheless took hold 
inflation dropped and leveled off at about 10 percent a year 
among south americas lowest rates in 1987 and 1988 the country 
enjoyed modest but steady economic growth for the first time in 
many years 
oncescarce foreign investment is picking up as is foreign aid 
some factories and new homes and office buildings are going up 
with new tax revenues the government is paving streets and 
painting public buildings 
bolivia is a country that has made a complete turnaround 
us ambassador robert gelbard said in an interview it has 
reversed the trend toward economic collapse and established the 
base for recovery 
gelbard said he expects the recovery to continue no matter which 
of the three candidates is chosen president since each is 
committed to the program 
im very optimistic 
fernando mendoza world bank representative in bolivia said the 
bolivian program represents a very important example for latin 
america and other countries that are passing through a similar 
situation 
while such countries as nearby brazil and argentina try to 
entangle themselves from foreign debt bolivia because of its 
poverty is under less pressure from foreign creditors 
unlike other debtor countries bolivia owes most of its 
42billion foreign debt to governments or international 
assistance agencies which have been more willing to reschedule 
payment 
commercial lenders have virtually written off the 700 million 
bolivia owes them and has allowed the government to buy half of it 
back at 11 percent of its face value 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

