<TEXT>
stage doors sometimes stick and smoke effects 
have gone up in flames costumes are homemade or handmedowns and 
actors race out the theaters back door through a parking lot and 
past derelicts on the street to make front stage entrances 
its all part of high opera in a distinctly lowbrow area called 
the bowery one of new york citys dingier spots 
with a 24hour car park on one side a transient hotel and 
punkrock club on the other the narrow fourstory amato opera 
theatre fills the bowery with strains of mozart and puccini 
this everymans opera company is the creation of tony amato who 
fell in love with opera as a youngster shortly after emigrating 
with his family from minori italy to the united states 
but the amato theaters unprepossessing style is no cover for 
amateurish ways since amato launched his opera theater 41 years 
ago 65 alumni have graduated to the metropolitan opera new york 
city opera and other companies in the united states 
he was a beacon for me there was a place i could go at a very 
young age and learn said neil shicoff a lead tenor at the met 
he went to amato when he was 19 after being rejected by the 
juilliard school after three years with the amato juilliard 
accepted him 
the learning techniques of how to act were really from tony 
the 39yearold shicoff recalled in a recent interview how to 
stand how to really look at another singer and how to not lose the 
audience when you do that or how not to sing directly to the side 
into the wings 
it was only when i sang on an international level that i 
realized how good tony was he really could take somebody from 
scratch and teach you stuff which a lot of directors cant do 
attracted by that reputation amatos amateur casts of hundreds 
trek over after office hours from throughout the city for a chance 
to learn operas heroic and obscure roles staging and later to 
perform fulllength operas before tiny audiences the converted 
storehouse seats about 100 folding chairs are set up for sellouts 
at the amato only the scenic designer and musicians are paid 
the amatos receive rent for the building an annual grant from the 
new york state council of the arts for 4000 ticket sales at 12 
each a handful of contract performances and contributions keep the 
shows running last years annual budget was the highest ever 
100000 the season usually includes five productions of about 10 
performances each 
people dont really do it for money said 24yearold mark 
freiman who made his debut in march as the lead in the marriage 
of figaro 
amato a short whirlwind of energy controls almost every aspect 
of his company he chooses the operas stages the productions 
directs the actors changes the scenery conducts the orchestra 
hes the master of ceremonies announcing winners of raffles for 
amato tshirts and videotaped operas during a performance of 
faust several years ago amato even put down the baton to 
extinguish a fire when a smoke effect went awry 
my theory is that to have good theater one man has to be in 
charge when you have a stage director a music director a scenic 
director and a costume director too much friction too much time 
wasted i experienced it many many years ago thats why i decided 
to do everything myself 
i used to be a singer i still sing once in a while in an 
emergency said the 68yearold amato who toured the united 
states with regional opera companies as a tenor 
opera in those days was very bad badly put together and i 
always realized the lack of good theater in it so when i had a 
chance to i started teaching to earn some extra income i realized 
how much i could give to it 
dubbed the twopenny opera in one newspaper account of the 
theaters history the amato seems to pride itself on making the 
most of less his wife sally helps wherever needed from sewing 
costumes to singing lastminute roles props are inventive dry 
oatmeal was used once for snow but discontinued when hordes of 
mice invaded sets are reused carefully patched up so age doesnt 
show 
the orchestra pit is literally that a cramped cellarlike area 
mostly under the stage with barely enough space for one upright 
piano and the usual accompaniment of 10 musicians the concession 
stand is a small table in the back of the room where amatos 
sisterinlaw sells coffee and homemade rum balls and cookies 
when scenes call for front stage entrances actors must race out 
the theaters back door through the parking lot past a varying 
assortment of vagrants alcoholics and drug addicts and in through 
the theaters front door 
amato moved his theater to the bowery 29 years ago instead of 
having dope addicts we had wine addicts amato said 
but theres been no trouble and sometimes he invites his 
neighbors of the street in for a show 
i say if you dress clean ill let you come in and they do 
youd be surprised the knowledge of opera some of them have its 
incredible he said 
the contrast between the art form and the neighborhood is often 
startling 
were always running around with our costumes on the bums 
they stare at you and sometimes they think they have had too much 
to drink freiman said usually when you wear your costume no 
one says anything because its new york 
but during one opera which required tie and tails several men 
asked freiman for money because they thought he was rich 
it was weird shicoff recalled i would sing a performance 
down there and i would feel on top of the world and you would walk 
outside and somebodys laying in the gutter its a very strange 
dichotomy of emotions 
despite its humble stature the amato sometimes attracts opera 
critics from such publications as the new york times and the new 
yorker especially when it puts on operas not often performed 
elsewhere the generally favorable reviews are plastered throughout 
the theater 
unlike some large opera companies which dazzle the spectator 
initially but then sputter the amato operas production pulls the 
listener in very gradually gaining momentum as it progresses 
wrote the times tim page in a review of offenbachs tales of 
hoffman in 1986 
amato used to have more grandiose aspirations than his spot on 
the bowery 
years ago i believe i had an ambition to get to the 
metropolitan he said but not for the past 20 years because i 
know i could do more here to help the young artists get ahead and 
learn the trade 
</TEXT>
