<TEXT>
ask russ mittermeier about his work and hell 
talk about marketing the hard sell tough choices and money just 
what you might expect from a sales executive or investment 
counselor 
mittermeier however is a wildlife biologist and vice president 
for science of the world wildlife fund hes talking about 
marketing conservation in countries where people struggle to find 
their next meal hes deciding how to get the most from a limited 
pool of conservation dollars 
his approach is a sign of a new discipline among 
conservationists as they try to sharpen the conservation blueprint 
for the 1990s 
i think weve got the potential to find the resources to make 
conservation work he said we really have to make good 
conservation an element of good development 
other conservationists are thinking along similar lines in 
january the world resources institute issued a report titled 
the crucial decade the 1990s and the global environmental 
challenge 
if efforts to save species and biological diversity are to 
succeed a more coordinated systematic and aggressive 
international effort is needed the report said the 1990s will 
be the crucial decade for action on these pressing concerns 
without a major effort it said irreparable damage will be 
done to the worlds environment and the problems will prove 
increasingly intractable expensive and dominated by crises 
mittermeier is trying to save endangered animals saving animals 
means saving habitat the most carefully protected animals cannot 
survive if they have no place to live 
so much has been said about the loss of habitat that the mere 
recitation of statistics has lost its force each year about 
42000 square miles of tropical forest are lost almost enough to 
cover the state of new york 
its anybodys guess how many plant and animal species are 
disappearing 
in a report titled biodiversity harvard biologist eo 
wilson tweaked the numbers and came up with this species are being 
lost 1000 to 10000 times as fast as they were before human beings 
arrived on the scene 
by the turn of the century much of the remaining tropical 
forest is going to be in isolated parks surrounded by 
development said mittermeier there will be very few places 
where natural evolutionary processes continue where traditional 
people continue to live traditional lifestyles 
mittermeier and his colleagues have established three lines of 
attack to try to limit the damage 
theyve identified 10 threatened hot spots small forested 
regions in immediate danger the hot spots cover twotenths of 1 
percent of the earths surface but harbor 27 percent of all 
tropical forest plant species 
theyve targeted 13 countries as megadiversity countries 
for their unusually rich animal and plant life these countries 
contain at least 60 percent of the worlds plant and animal species 
and theyve identified what they call major wilderness areas 
the few places still mostly undisturbed where if steps are taken 
soon evolution can continue and traditional people can survive 
the threatened hot spots idea came from norman myers a 
senior fellow at the world wildlife fund 
without emergency aid the 10 hot spots are likely to lose 
90 percent of their forest cover within the next decade that would 
mean losing almost 7 percent of the earths 5 million to 30 million 
plant and animal species 
apart from madagascar and new caledonia the threatened hot 
spots are in south american and asia south americas are in the 
choco region of colombia western ecuador the uplands of western 
amazonia and the atlantic coast of brazil 
asias are in the philippines northern borneo malaysia and the 
eastern himalayas 
many of the species in these areas have already been lost or 
will soon be lost even if the areas are left untouched from now 
on myers said the rule of thumb is that for half of the species 
to survive the remaining forest must cover at least 10 percent of 
its original range 
myers says that is hardly ever the case 
mittermeier developed the concept of megadiversity countries 
as a marketing device its tremendously valuable he said it 
can be used in the megadiversity countries to excite the public 
about conservation 
its a source of national pride he said it tells them 
in terms of natural resources were pretty special its an 
effective way of selling conservation to them and to 
foundations 
because these countries contain at least 60 percent and perhaps 
even 80 percent of the worlds species they ought to get 60 
percent or 70 percent of conservation funds mittermeier has 
proposed 
the countries are mexico venezuela colombia ecuador peru 
brazil zaire madagascar indonesia australia india china and 
malaysia 
mittermeier whose research specialty is primates said brazil 
zaire indonesia and madagascar contain twothirds of the worlds 
primate species if we arent successful in saving primate 
species in these countries were going to lose a major portion of 
the species he said 
were not writing off the rest of the world were saying do 
something in every country on earth but strategically when we do 
our planning these countries should get a major chunk of the 
interest a major chunk of the investment 
there is some good news in this story mittermeier and company 
have identified five major wilderness areas that have a good chance 
of survival 
these areas are not under immediate threat he said it 
wont require a large investment to save them you just have to 
point out to the countries that this is something you should invest 
in for the future he said 
they are in new guinea central zaire venezuela south of the 
orinoco river parts of upper amazonia and in a region that cuts 
across southern suriname guyana and french guiana 
the other bit of good news is that the world bank where 
mittermeier has served as manager of a task force on biodiversity 
takes conservation seriously 
the banks mission traditionally has been to foster development 
in poor countries which often put it in conflict with 
environmentalists it made an important change in 1986 with the 
adoption of a wildlands policy 
wildlands can often contribute significantly to economic 
development the bank said the banks policy is therefore to 
seek a balance between preserving the environmental values of the 
worlds more important remaining wildlands and converting some of 
them to more intensive shorter term use 
mittermeier said conservationists should do two things to try to 
save remaining forests the first is to expand the number and size 
of protected areas but that has its limitations 
they are expensive and will compose at best only five to 10 
percent of the worlds land area mittermeier said 
the second tactic is to encourage profitable use of the forests 
that doesnt destroy them researchers recently found for example 
that harvesting latex fruit and wood from a managed forest was 
three times as profitable as cutting it down to produce pulpwood or 
raise crops or cattle mittermeier said 
development inevitably comes back to depending on natural 
resources he said and if you dont use natural resources 
wisely your development efforts and your global economy are 
eventually going to go down the tube 
