a surge in the dollar and an improved outlook 
for inflation propelled bond prices sharply higher and drove 
interest rates downward monday 
the treasurys bellwether 30year bond was up 1316 point or 
nearly 12 for every 1000 in face value its yield fell to 859 
percent the lowest closing yield since march 1988 and was down 
from 870 percent on friday bond prices and yields move in 
opposite directions 
the dollar broke an important psychological barrier 2 west 
german marks and hit a 1year high against the japanese yen 
despite repeated intervention by central banks and a plea from the 
white house to depress the us currency 
the dollars surge helped spark a sharp drop in commodity 
prices and that in turn increased bond traders hopes that 
inflation would slow down and the economy would cool off analysts 
said 
when the economy is slow the federal reserve board is less 
likely to tighten credit which raises interest rates and sends 
bond prices lower 
mitchell held chief financial economist with smith barney 
harris upham amp co said money that had flowed out of bonds as 
interest rates rose was changing direction and moving back into 
treasury securities 
people are realizng the economy is slowing down he said 
people are underinvested in bonds 
